			<div class="normtxt clr lh16 tljust" style="padding-top:10px;">
			<b>Dr KM Cherian: Pioneering heart surgeon</b><br><br>
				<img src="http://img.christianmatrimony.com/images/christian/prideimg.jpg" style="padding-right:12px;float:left;"/>Dr KM Cherian is an outstanding heart surgeon of international repute. He has pioneered new treatments, founded new hospitals and is credited with performing the first coronary artery bypass surgery in India in 1975. He has also performed the country's second heart transplant, first infant cardiac surgery and the first heart and lung transplant (1999).<br><br>
				Dr. Cherian has performed more than 32,000 operations, a unique record in itself, and has been called the father of pediatric cardiac surgery in the country.<br><br>
				Dr Cherian is the first and only Indian member of the prestigious American Association for Thoracic Surgery, as well as a fellow of the Royal Society of Medicine, London and a member of the Malaysian Association for Thoracic and Cardiovascular Surgery, just to mention a few of his affiliations.<br><br>
				Dr Cherian was honorary surgeon to the President of India from 1990 to 1993. He was awarded Padma Shri by the Government of India in 1991. He received a Wockhardt Medical Excellence Award in 2005, through a panel organized by Harvard Medical School. He has also been honoured with honorary professorships from universities in China. <br><br>
				Dr Cherian has authored more than 285 national and international publications, co-authored books on pediatric cardiac surgery and is the only Asian author to contribute to the Textbook of Cardiac Surgery, an essential bible to all cardiac surgeons.<br><br>
				His is also the first and only Indian's name engraved in one of the stones at Kos Island, Greece, the birth place of the medical profession and Hippocrates, the "Father of Medicine".<br><br>
				Dr Cherian's charitable endeavours were recognized by Mother Teresa, who appreciated his intense efforts and had constantly referred poor patients to him.<br><br>
				The President of India in his appeal to the Iraqi abductors, who had kidnapped three Indians, cited Dr Cherian's humanitarian gesture of operating on 20 Iraqi children who came with complex congenital heart defects in March the same year at the Frontier Lifeline, Chennai. <br><br>
				Dr Cherian was the recipient of the prestigious Doctor of Science (Honoris Causa) degree, awarded by King George's Medical University, Lucknow, during its 3rd Convocation in 2007. <br><br>
				The International Centre for Cardiothoracic and Vascular Diseases started by Frontier Lifeline is yet another brainchild of Dr Cherian. This institution provides state-of-the-art facilities in cardiac diagnosis, treatment, research and education at an affordable cost. <br><br>
				Dr Cherian is also an advocate for organ donation and is the leading authority in heart transplant procedures in the country. His philosophy is summed up in the following line:  "Health care is an industry but care of the sick is not an industry."<br><br>
